00:24:17,300 --> 00:24:18,260
Mom.

273
00:24:18,380 --> 00:24:20,380
They were both exactly
as lovely as each other.

274
00:24:20,420 --> 00:24:22,180
l think you better
blow the candles out

275
00:24:22,260 --> 00:24:23,260
before the cake catches fire.

276
00:24:23,340 --> 00:24:25,860
Wait until they do you
a candle for each decade, dear.

277
00:24:25,980 --> 00:24:28,500
Then you'll know
you're past it.

278
00:24:33,380 --> 00:24:34,940
Didn't forget to make a wish.

279
00:24:37,420 --> 00:24:38,500
Got it.

280
00:24:39,820 --> 00:24:40,820
Oh!

281
00:24:44,780 --> 00:24:49,540
Mom, when are we going
to open the presents?

282
00:24:49,620 --> 00:24:50,860
Now.

283
00:24:50,980 --> 00:24:52,860
Many of you know her
from her work

284
00:24:52,940 --> 00:24:54,660
with the Elliott Hauser
Foundation

285
00:24:54,700 --> 00:24:57,020
for the lnternational Promotion
of Human Rights.

286
00:24:57,100 --> 00:24:58,860
ln more recent years however,

287
00:24:58,940 --> 00:25:01,140
she has become an active
lobbyist at Whitehall

288
00:25:01,220 --> 00:25:04,900
on issues of asylum
and refugee protection.

289
00:25:04,940 --> 00:25:07,780
Ladies and gentlemen,
it gives me great pleasure

290
00:25:07,820 --> 00:25:10,580
to introduce
our new spokesperson

291
00:25:10,660 --> 00:25:12,620
for the UNHCR
in the United Kingdom,

292
00:25:12,700 --> 00:25:15,060
Mrs. Sarah Bauford.

293
00:25:27,220 --> 00:25:29,220
Thank you.

294
00:25:30,740 --> 00:25:33,060
Thank you.

295
00:25:33,140 --> 00:25:34,460
Ladies and gentlemen,

296
00:25:34,540 --> 00:25:39,700
l feel very nervous to be
standing in front of you today.

297
00:25:39,780 --> 00:25:42,540
l also feel very honored.

298
00:25:42,580 --> 00:25:44,940
ln particular, because
UNHCR was the organization

299
00:25:44,980 --> 00:25:49,580
to which l was first introduced
by my friend Elliott Hauser.

300
00:25:49,620 --> 00:25:51,060
l know that my being
offered this post

301
00:25:51,140 --> 00:25:52,660
would have given him
enormous pleasure.

302
00:25:52,740 --> 00:25:56,340
Over 50 million people

303
00:25:56,420 --> 00:26:00,100
are refugees or displaced
persons in the world today.

304
00:26:00,140 --> 00:26:03,140
And because of closed minds
and funding shortfalls,

305
00:26:03,220 --> 00:26:06,540
we are only able to reach
half of those in need.

306
00:26:15,020 --> 00:26:17,980
So we rely on our partners,

307
00:26:18,060 --> 00:26:20,780
the network of aid groups
blazing a trail across crises,

308
00:26:20,820 --> 00:26:24,420
like El Salvador, Angola,

309
00:26:24,460 --> 00:26:27,700
Chechnya, Sri Lanka...

310
00:26:27,780 --> 00:26:31,740
those NGO's, the non-
governmental groups from OXFAM

311
00:26:31,780 --> 00:26:33,140
right down
to the smallest outfits

312
00:26:33,220 --> 00:26:34,580
run by people like Elliott
and...

313
00:26:41,620 --> 00:26:44,580
...and l pray for those
who survive him--

314
00:26:44,620 --> 00:26:46,420
who continue his work--

315
00:26:46,500 --> 00:26:48,860
without certainty or security--

316
00:26:48,940 --> 00:26:51,660
wherever they may be
in this world.

317
00:26:54,380 --> 00:26:55,860
Excuse me.

318
00:27:08,060 --> 00:27:09,420
Hey.

319
00:27:09,500 --> 00:27:10,700
Hey.

320
00:27:10,780 --> 00:27:11,900
Thanks for coming.

321
00:27:11,980 --> 00:27:13,580
Listen, l travel
thousands of miles

322
00:27:13,660 --> 00:27:15,140
to hear my sister
give a speech,

323
00:27:15,220 --> 00:27:16,580
l got a backache and jet lag.

324
00:27:16,620 --> 00:27:18,100
What's a taxi ride to the park?

325
00:27:18,180 --> 00:27:20,180
Sorry.
Are they angry?

326
00:27:20,260 --> 00:27:21,780
No. They don't care, Sarah.

327
00:27:21,860 --> 00:27:23,740
l think they actually
kind of enjoyed it.

328
00:27:23,820 --> 00:27:26,100
''She's nuts'' makes
for much better conversation

329
00:27:26,180 --> 00:27:27,500
than ''Nice speech.''

330
00:27:27,540 --> 00:27:29,860
l got a letter from Nick,

331
00:27:29,940 --> 00:27:32,580
and l think he's in trouble.

332
00:27:32,660 --> 00:27:34,660
Why? What did he say?

333
00:27:34,700 --> 00:27:36,780
Nothing, really.
Just little things.

334
00:27:38,020 --> 00:27:39,420
Well, where is he?

335
00:27:39,460 --> 00:27:40,780
He's in Chechnya.

336
00:27:40,820 --> 00:27:42,980
He's running
some sort of camp.

337
00:27:43,060 --> 00:27:44,500
l'm really not sure.

338
00:27:45,820 --> 00:27:47,020
l need to find him.

339
00:27:47,100 --> 00:27:48,500
So, you have contacts.

340
00:27:48,580 --> 00:27:50,420
You can find out where he is.

341
00:27:50,500 --> 00:27:51,900
So, please?

342
00:27:51,980 --> 00:27:54,220
Sarah, sweetheart,
you know as well as l do

343
00:27:54,300 --> 00:27:57,660
that Chechnya is
a very dangerous place.

344
00:28:03,780 --> 00:28:06,380
Yes, l can angle
a story there, l'm sure.

345
00:28:06,460 --> 00:28:09,700
lf l find out anything,
l will let you know. Okay?

346
00:28:10,700 --> 00:28:12,940
Okay. Okay.

347
00:28:13,020 --> 00:28:14,380
Okay.

348
00:28:14,460 --> 00:28:15,860
Thank you.

349
00:28:19,940 --> 00:28:23,740
Perhaps we are all refugees
from something,

350
00:28:23,860 --> 00:28:26,980
but l see now
there is nothing to fear;

351
00:28:27,060 --> 00:28:31,180
that the world we hold on to,
the lives we cherish,

352
00:28:31,220 --> 00:28:35,820
are a part of something greater
--something more.

353
00:28:35,860 --> 00:28:39,140
When l look at my children,
l see it so clearly--

354
00:28:39,220 --> 00:28:40,740
that hope--

355
00:28:40,820 --> 00:28:43,140
that chance of life--

356
00:28:43,220 --> 00:28:45,420
and l know
it's worth fighting for.

357
00:28:46,580 --> 00:28:49,060
''The wedding was
a splendid affair.

358
00:28:49,140 --> 00:28:51,020
''Everyone attended--

359
00:28:51,060 --> 00:28:53,700
''the dwarves, and the
animals of the forest--

360
00:28:53,780 --> 00:28:55,260
''and there were tears of joy

361
00:28:55,300 --> 00:28:56,580
''and songs of happiness,

362
00:28:56,620 --> 00:28:58,340
''and the prince
and the princess

363
00:28:58,420 --> 00:29:01,540
lived happily ever after.''

364
00:29:01,620 --> 00:29:04,100
How does it really end, Mummy?

365
00:29:04,180 --> 00:29:05,580
What do you mean?

366
00:29:05,620 --> 00:29:07,660
What do you think happens,
honey?

367
00:29:07,740 --> 00:29:11,340
She wakes up,
looks at the prince,

368
00:29:11,420 --> 00:29:14,580
